---
pagination:
  data: industries.categories
  size: 1
  alias: category
permalink: "/valuation/{{ category.slug }}/"
---
{%- extends "layouts/base.njk" -%}


{# ─── Front-matter computed values ─────────────────────────────────────────── #}
{%- set pageTitle = category.name + " Business Valuation: SDE Multiples & Market Data (" + site.dataYear + ")" -%}
{%- set metaDescription = category.name + " businesses sell for " + category.multiple_low + "× to " + category.multiple_high + "× SDE depending on type. Valuation data for " + category.industry_count + " business types, based on BizBuySell transaction records." -%}
{%- set canonicalPath = category.url -%}

{# ─── Schema ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── #}
{% block schema %}
  {% include "schema/category.njk" %}
{% endblock %}

{# ─── Page content ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── #}
{% block content %}

{# ── Breadcrumb ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── #}
<nav class="breadcrumb" aria-label="Breadcrumb">
  <ol>
    <li><a href="/">Home</a></li>
    <li><a href="/valuation/">Business Valuation</a></li>
    <li aria-current="page">{{ category.name }}</li>
  </ol>
</nav>

{# ── H1 + Overview ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── #}
<section class="category-hero">
  <div class="container">
    <h1>Valuing a {{ category.name }} Business: SDE Multiples and {{ site.dataYear }} Market Data</h1>
    <div class="category-overview">
      <p>
        {{ category.name }} businesses sell across a wide range of valuations — from
        <strong>{{ category.multiple_low }}×</strong> to <strong>{{ category.multiple_high }}×</strong>
        annual SDE — depending on the specific type of business, the degree of owner involvement,
        and the strength of recurring revenue.
      </p>
      <p>
        This page covers all {{ category.industry_count }} {{ category.name }} business types tracked
        in Mainstreet Benchmark's transaction database, sourced from {{ site.transactionCount }}+ closed
        sales reported to BizBuySell. Each business type has its own multiple derived from its actual
        transaction history — not a generic estimate.
      </p>
      <p>
        Use our free
        <a href="/">business valuation calculator</a>
        to get your industry-specific estimate, adjusted for your revenue trend, owner involvement,
        and customer concentration.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

{# ── Multiple Summary Table ──────────────────────────────────────────────────── #}
<section class="category-table-section">
  <div class="container">
    <h2>{{ category.name }} Business Valuation Multiples by Type</h2>

    <div class="data-table-wrap">
      <table class="data-table category-table">
        <caption class="sr-only">SDE multiples for all {{ category.name }} business types from BizBuySell closed transaction data</caption>
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th scope="col">Business Type</th>
            <th scope="col">Typical SDE Multiple</th>
            <th scope="col">Transactions</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          {% for ind in category.industries %}
          <tr>
            <td>
              <a href="{{ ind.page_url }}">{{ ind.industry_name }}</a>
            </td>
            <td>{{ ind.sde_multiple_low }}× – {{ ind.sde_multiple_high }}× <span class="median-note">({{ ind.sde_multiple_mid }}× median)</span></td>
            <td>{{ ind.transaction_count }}+</td>
          </tr>
          {% endfor %}
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <p class="table-source-note">
      Source: <a href="{{ site.bizBuySellUrl }}" target="_blank" rel="noopener">BizBuySell Industry Valuation Report</a>,
      {{ site.dataSource }}. Multiples reflect closed transaction prices, not asking prices.
    </p>
  </div>
</section>

{# ── Industry Deep-Dives ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────── #}
<section class="industry-deep-dives">
  <div class="container">

    {% for ind in category.industries %}
    <div class="deep-dive">
      <h2>{{ ind.industry_name }} Businesses</h2>
      <p>
        {{ ind.industry_name }} businesses sell for <strong>{{ ind.sde_multiple_low }}× to {{ ind.sde_multiple_high }}×</strong>
        SDE, with a median of {{ ind.sde_multiple_mid }}×, based on {{ ind.transaction_count }}+ closed transactions.
        {{ ind.deal_notes | truncate(200, true, "…") }}
      </p>
      <a href="{{ ind.page_url }}" class="deep-dive__cta">
        See full {{ ind.industry_name }} valuation data →
      </a>
    </div>
    {% endfor %}

  </div>
</section>

{# ── Key Factors ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── #}
<section class="category-factors">
  <div class="container">
    <h2>Key Factors Affecting {{ category.name }} Business Valuations</h2>
    <p>
      Across all {{ category.industry_count }} {{ category.name }} business types, buyers and their lenders
      evaluate the same core set of risk and quality signals when underwriting an acquisition.
      Understanding these factors — before you list — determines whether you sell at the median
      or at the upper quartile of your industry's multiple range.
    </p>

    <h3>Recurring Revenue and Customer Retention</h3>
    <p>
      Businesses with predictable, recurring revenue — service contracts, membership programs, or long-term
      accounts — command meaningfully higher multiples than comparable businesses with transactional revenue.
      Buyers pay for certainty. A {{ category.name }} business that can demonstrate 60%+ customer return rates
      or contract-based revenue is valued as a less risky acquisition and priced accordingly.
    </p>

    <h3>Owner Dependency</h3>
    <p>
      The single most common value discount across all {{ category.name }} transactions is owner dependency.
      When the owner is the primary service provider, holds key relationships, or is the face of the business
      to major customers, buyers must price in the cost of replacing that role. Systematized businesses —
      where operations run via documented processes, trained staff, and accountable managers — command the
      upper quartile. The full calculator applies a ±0.20× adjustment for owner involvement, which equals
      $40,000–$60,000 on a $200,000–$300,000 SDE business.
    </p>

    <h3>Financial Documentation Quality</h3>
    <p>
      SBA lenders require 3 years of business tax returns and internally prepared P&amp;Ls. {{ category.name }}
      businesses with clean, consistent financial records sell faster and at higher prices because buyers and
      their lenders can underwrite the acquisition with confidence. Businesses with cash income not reported
      on tax returns, inconsistent bookkeeping, or owner-managed financial records face significant buyer
      skepticism — and discounts or deal failures during diligence.
    </p>

    <h3>Lease and Location Security</h3>
    <p>
      For location-dependent {{ category.name }} businesses, lease terms are a primary deal risk.
      A business with a lease expiring within 12 months of closing — and no renewal option — faces buyers
      who either walk or heavily discount for the risk. Securing a 5+ year remaining lease with a renewal
      option before going to market removes a major diligence friction point and supports full-multiple pricing.
    </p>

    <p>
      <a href="/guides/how-to-prepare-business-for-sale/">How to Prepare Your Business for Sale →</a>
    </p>
  </div>
</section>

{# ── Ad Unit ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── #}
<div class="ad-unit ad-unit--mid-content" aria-label="Advertisement">
  <div class="ad-unit__inner">
    <ins class="adsbygoogle"
         style="display:block;min-height:280px;"
         data-ad-client="ca-pub-XXXXXXXXXXXXXXXX"
         data-ad-slot="XXXXXXXXXX"
         data-ad-format="auto"
         data-full-width-responsive="true"></ins>
  </div>
</div>

{# ── FAQ ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── #}
<section class="category-faq">
  <div class="container">
    <h2>Frequently Asked Questions: {{ category.name }} Business Valuations</h2>

    <div class="faq-list">

      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>What SDE multiple do {{ category.name }} businesses sell for?</h3>
        <p>
          According to Mainstreet Benchmark's analysis of BizBuySell transaction data, {{ category.name }}
          businesses typically sell for <strong>{{ category.multiple_low }}× to {{ category.multiple_high }}×</strong>
          annual SDE, with a median around {{ category.multiple_mid_avg }}×. The range reflects the
          {{ category.industry_count }} distinct business types within this category — each with its own
          multiple driven by recurring revenue, owner dependency, and customer concentration.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>How many {{ category.name }} business types are covered in your data?</h3>
        <p>
          Mainstreet Benchmark covers {{ category.industry_count }} {{ category.name }} business types,
          each with its own SDE multiple range derived from BizBuySell closed transaction records.
          Use the links in the table above to view industry-specific multiples, transaction counts,
          and market context for each type.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>How do I calculate the value of my {{ category.name }} business?</h3>
        <p>
          The standard method for valuing a {{ category.name }} business is to multiply annual SDE
          (Seller's Discretionary Earnings) by the industry-specific multiple. Select your specific
          business type from the table above to see its current multiple range, then enter your SDE
          and revenue into the <a href="/">free calculator</a> to receive a personalized valuation
          range adjusted for growth trend, owner involvement, and customer concentration.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>What is SDE and how is it different from net profit?</h3>
        <p>
          SDE — Seller's Discretionary Earnings — equals net profit plus the owner's salary plus
          any personal expenses run through the business plus non-cash charges like depreciation.
          For most {{ category.name }} businesses, SDE is 15–35% higher than reported net profit.
          It is the standard valuation basis for Main Street businesses because it normalizes for
          the fact that owners structure their compensation differently — some pay themselves market
          salaries, others take minimal salary and maximize distributions.
          <a href="/guides/what-is-sde/">Full SDE calculation guide →</a>
        </p>
      </div>

    </div>
  </div>
</section>

{# ── BizBuySell Citation ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────── #}
<aside class="data-citation">
  <div class="container">
    <p>
      Transaction data: <a href="{{ site.bizBuySellUrl }}" target="_blank" rel="noopener">BizBuySell Industry Valuation Report</a>,
      {{ site.dataSource }}. Covering {{ site.transactionCount }}+ closed transactions across
      {{ site.dataYear }} categories. This tool provides planning estimates only and does not
      constitute a formal business appraisal.
    </p>
  </div>
</aside>

{% endblock %}
